nd, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bradshaw","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the three places called Bradshaw in Lancashire, Yorkshire, and Derbyshire, from Old English <i>brād</i> ‘broad’ + <i>sceaga</i> ‘thicket’."],"variants":[{"name":"Brayshaw","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Bradshaw  , reflecting the local Yorkshire pronunciation."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Bradshaw was born about 1314, in Swillington, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Mrs William Bradshaw about 1339, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1314–":"umbes 1314–Surnud","1314–Female":"1314–Surnud","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","1314–Male":"1314–Surnud","1314":"1314","about 1339":"umbes 1339","1355":"1355","about 1314":"umbes 1314","about 1355":"umbes 1355","of Nether, Swillington, Yorkshire, England":"Swillington, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Nether, Swillington, West Riding of Yorkshire,n England":"Swillington, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{